{"title_page": "John Finch (died 1763)", "text_new": "'''John Finch''' (c. 1692\u201312 February 1763) of Bushey, Hertfordshire,  was a British lawyer and politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] for 23 years from 1724 to 1747.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Mills and Rowland whipping Richard Hawkins to death Wellcome L0040924.jpg|thumb|Sally Salisbury wounding the Honourable Mr F----]]\nFinch was the third son of [[Daniel Finch, 2nd Earl of Nottingham]] and 7th Earl of Winchilsea and his second wife [[Anne Finch, Countess of Nottingham|Anne Hatton]], daughter of [[Christopher Hatton, 1st Viscount Hatton]]. He was educated at [[Eton College]] from 1706 to 1707 and matriculated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]] on 26 January 1708, aged 15.<ref name=ALUM>{{cite web |url = https://www.british-history.ac.uk/alumni-oxon/1500-1714/pp480-509  |title= Faber-Flood in Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714 pp. 480-509  | author= Foster, Joseph |publisher= British History Online|    accessdate = 7 December 2018 }}</ref>  In 1711, he was admitted at [[Inner Temple]], and was called to the bar in 1719. He became known as \u2018him who was stabbed by [[Sally Salisbury]]\u2019 after an incident on the night of 18 December 1722, when a prostitute, Sally Pridden (known as Salisbury), stabbed  him at the Three Tuns tavern in Chandos Street, apparently in a fit of passion during an argument over theatre tickets.<ref>{{cite book|title=Letters from the Right Honourable Lady Mary Wortley Montagu 1709 to 1762|author=Lady Mary Wortley Montagu|publisher=Kessinger Publishing|page=564|year=2005|isbn=978-1-4179-0741-0}}</ref> She was found guilty of assault and wounding, without intent to kill, and was fined and sent to Newgate prison<ref>\n[https://www.oldbaileyonline.org/images.jsp?doc=172304240008  The Proceedings of the Old Bailey \u2013 Proceedings 24 April 1713.]</ref> where she died in 1724. He later married an actress, [[Elizabeth Younger]] after she had an illegitimate daughter by him.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/finch-hon-john-1692-1763 | title=FINCH, Hon. John (?1692-1763), of Bushey, Herts | publisher= History of Parliament Online | accessdate = 7 December  2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFinch stood unsuccessfully at a by-election on  1 June 1723 at [[Maidstone (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidstone]] on the interest of his cousin, [[Heneage Finch, 2nd Earl of Aylesford]] whose brother, another [[John Finch (died 1740)|John Finch]] was a sitting member. He was elected as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Higham Ferrers (UK Parliament constituency)|Higham Ferrers]] on the interest of his brother-in-law, [[Thomas Watson Wentworth]] at a by-election on 20 January 1724. He was solicitor general to the Prince of Wales from 1726 to 1727 and became [[King's Counsel]] (KC) in 1727 when the Prince became King George II. At the [[1727 British general election|1727 general election]], he was returned unopposed for Higham Ferrers.  In Parliament he followed his brother [[Daniel Finch, 8th Earl of Winchilsea|Lord Finch]]. He seconding the Address in 1729 and joined his brother in opposition in 1730. He was again returned unopposed at the [[1734 British general election|1734]]. He was Treasure of his Inn in 1739. At the  [[1741 British general election|1741 general election]]  he made way for his brother [[Henry Finch (died 1761)|Henry]] at Higham Ferrers, and transferred to [[Rutland (UK Parliament constituency)|Rutland]]  where he was returned unopposed as MP with the support of his elder brother, now Lord Winchilsea. After Walpole's fall in 1742,  he and his brothers supported the Government and in 1746 he was classed as one of Granville's followers. Lord Winchilsea intended to put him up for Rutland again at the [[1747 British general election|1747 general election]]  but realised he had little chance of success. Finch never stood for Parliament again.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nFinch died on 12 February 1763, leaving a daughter born before marriage, whose presentation at court in 1747 created controversy in the family. As well as Lord Finch and Henry, his brothers [[Edward Finch (diplomat)|Edward]] and [[William Finch (diplomat)|William Finch]] were also Members of Parliament.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Thomas Watson Wentworth]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n| title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Higham Ferrers (UK Parliament constituency)|Higham Ferrers]]\n | years =    1724\u2013[[1741 British general election|1741]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Henry Finch (died 1761)|Henry Finch]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[James Noel (MP)|James Noel]]\n | before2 = [[Thomas Noel (MP)|Thomas Noel]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n| title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Rutland (UK Parliament constituency)|Rutland]]\n | years =   [[1741 British general election|1741]]\u2013[[1747 British general election|1747]]\n| with  =  [[James Noel (MP)|James Noel]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[James Noel (MP)|James Noel]]\n | after2 = [[Brownlow Cecil, 9th Earl of Exeter|Lord Burghley]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finch, John}}\n[[Category:1690s births]]\n[[Category:1763 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1722\u20131727]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1734\u20131741]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1741\u20131747]]\n[[Category:Stabbing attacks in London]]\n[[Category:Younger sons of earls]]\n[[Category:Finch-Hatton family]]\n[[Category:Stabbing survivors]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Finch''' (c. 1692\u201312 February 1763) of Bushey, Hertfordshire,  was a British lawyer and politician who sat in the [[British House of Commons|House of Commons]] for 23 years from 1724 to 1747.\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Mills and Rowland whipping Richard Hawkins to death Wellcome L0040924.jpg|thumb|Sally Salisbury wounding the Honourable Mr F----]]\nFinch was the third son of [[Daniel Finch, 2nd Earl of Nottingham]] and 7th Earl of Winchilsea and his second wife [[Anne Finch, Countess of Nottingham|Anne Hatton]], daughter of [[Christopher Hatton, 1st Viscount Hatton]]. He was educated at [[Eton College]] from 1706 to 1707 and matriculated at [[Christ Church, Oxford]] on 26 January 1708, aged 15.<ref name=ALUM>{{cite web |url = https://www.british-history.ac.uk/alumni-oxon/1500-1714/pp480-509  |title= Faber-Flood in Alumni Oxonienses 1500-1714 pp. 480-509  | author= Foster, Joseph |publisher= British History Online|    accessdate = 7 December 2018 }}</ref>  In 1711, he was admitted at [[Inner Temple]], and was called to the bar in 1719. He became known as \u2018him who was stabbed by [[Sally Salisbury]]\u2019 after an incident on the night of 18 December 1722, when a prostitute, Sally Pridden (known as Salisbury), stabbed  him at the Three Tuns tavern in Chandos Street, apparently in a fit of passion during an argument over theatre tickets.<ref>{{cite book|title=Letters from the Right Honourable Lady Mary Wortley Montagu 1709 to 1762|author=Lady Mary Wortley Montagu|publisher=Kessinger Publishing|page=564|year=2005|isbn=978-1-4179-0741-0}}</ref> She was found guilty of assault and wounding, without intent to kill, and was fined and sent to Newgate prison<ref>\n[https://www.oldbaileyonline.org/images.jsp?doc=172304240008  The Proceedings of the Old Bailey \u2013 Proceedings 24 April 1713.]</ref> where she died in 1724. He later married an actress, [[Elizabeth Younger]] after she had an illegitimate daughter by him.<ref name = HOP>{{cite web| url = http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1715-1754/member/finch-hon-john-1692-1763 | title=FINCH, Hon. John (?1692-1763), of Bushey, Herts | publisher= History of Parliament Online | accessdate = 7 December  2018}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nFinch stood unsuccessfully at a by-election on  1 June 1723 at [[Maidstone (UK Parliament constituency)|Maidstone]] on the interest of his cousin, [[Heneage Finch, 2nd Earl of Aylesford]] whose brother, another [[John Finch (died 1740)|John Finch]] was a sitting member. He was elected as [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Higham Ferrers (UK Parliament constituency)|Higham Ferrers]] on the interest of his brother-in-law, [[Thomas Watson Wentworth]] at a by-election on 20 January 1724. He was solicitor general to the Prince of Wales from 1726 to 1727 and became [[King's Counsel]] (KC) in 1727 when the Prince became King George II. At the [[1727 British general election|1727 general election]], he was returned unopposed for Higham Ferrers.  In Parliament he followed his brother [[Daniel Finch, 8th Earl of Winchilsea|Lord Finch]]. He seconding the Address in 1729 and joined his brother in opposition in 1730. He was again returned unopposed at the [[1734 British general election|1734]]. He was Treasure of his Inn in 1739. At the  [[1741 British general election|1741 general election]]  he made way for his brother [[Henry Finch (died 1761)|Henry]] at Higham Ferrers, and transferred to [[Rutland (UK Parliament constituency)|Rutland]]  where he was returned unopposed as MP with the support of his elder brother, now Lord Winchilsea. After Walpole\u2019s fall in 1742,  he and his brothers supported the Government and in 1746 he was classed as one of Granville\u2019s followers. Lord Winchilsea intended to put him up for Rutland again at the [[1747 British general election|1747 general election]]  but realised he had little chance of success. Finch never stood for Parliament again.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==Death and legacy==\nFinch died on 12 February 1763, leaving a daughter born before marriage, whose presentation at court in 1747 created controversy in the family. As well as Lord Finch and Henry, his brothers [[Edward Finch (diplomat)|Edward]] and [[William Finch (diplomat)|William Finch]] were also Members of Parliament.<ref name=HOP/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|gb}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[Thomas Watson Wentworth]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n| title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Higham Ferrers (UK Parliament constituency)|Higham Ferrers]]\n | years =    1724\u2013[[1741 British general election|1741]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[Henry Finch (died 1761)|Henry Finch]]\n}}\n{{s-bef\n | before  = [[James Noel (MP)|James Noel]]\n | before2 = [[Thomas Noel (MP)|Thomas Noel]]\n}}\n{{s-title\n| title =  [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Rutland (UK Parliament constituency)|Rutland]]\n | years =   [[1741 British general election|1741]]\u2013[[1747 British general election|1747]]\n| with  =  [[James Noel (MP)|James Noel]]\n}}\n{{s-aft\n | after  = [[James Noel (MP)|James Noel]]\n | after2 = [[Brownlow Cecil, 9th Earl of Exeter|Lord Burghley]]\n}}\n\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Finch, John}}\n[[Category:1690s births]]\n[[Category:1763 deaths]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Christ Church, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of Great Britain for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1722\u20131727]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1727\u20131734]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1734\u20131741]]\n[[Category:British MPs 1741\u20131747]]\n[[Category:Stabbing attacks in London]]\n[[Category:Younger sons of earls]]\n[[Category:Finch-Hatton family]]\n[[Category:Stabbing survivors]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer:clean up,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Finch_(died_1763)"}
