          = <ref name=\"2015Est\">Khabarovsk Krai Territorial Branch of the [[Russian Federal State Statistics Service|Federal State Statistics Service]]. [http://habstat.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/habstat/resources/813ae78047b1995181a4a5ed3bc4492f/%D0%9C%D0%9E_01_2015.htm \u0427\u0438\u0441\u043b\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0441\u0442\u044c \u043d\u0430\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u0440\u0430\u044f \u043f\u043e \u043c\u0443\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043f\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u044b\u043c \u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0437\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f\u043c \u043d\u0430 1 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2015 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305044938/http://habstat.gks.ru/wps/wcm/connect/rosstat_ts/habstat/resources/813ae78047b1995181a4a5ed3bc4492f/%D0%9C%D0%9E_01_2015.htm |date=March 5, 2016 }} {{in lang|ru}}</ref>\n| population_demonym      = \n| time_zone_ref           = \n<!-- history -->\n| established_date        = May&nbsp;31, 1858\n| established_title       = \n| established_date_ref    = <ref name=\"HolidayEst\" />\n| current_cat_date        = 1880\n| current_cat_date_ref    = <ref name=\"gr\" />\n| abolished_date          = \n| abolished_date_ref      = \n<!-- misc -->\n| postal_codes            = 680000\u2013680003, 680006, 680007, 680009, 680011\u2013680015, 680017, 680018, 680020\u2013680023, 680025, 680026, 680028\u2013680033, 680035, 680038, 680040\u2013680043, 680045, 680047, 680051, 680052, 680054, 680055, 680700, 680880, 680890, 680899, 680921, 680950, 680960\u2013680967, 680970, 680999, 901183, 901185\n| postal_codes_ref        = \n| dialing_codes           = 4212\n| dialing_codes_ref       = \n| website                 = http://khabarovskadm.ru\n|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox\n|bodystyle=width:23.5em;\n|title=Khabarovsk population\n|label1=[[Russian Census (2010)|2010 Census]]\n|data1=577,441<ref name=\"2010Census\" />\n|label2=[[Russian Census (2002)|2002 Census]]\n|data2=583,072<ref name=\"2002Census\">{{ru-pop-ref|2002Census}}</ref>\n|label3=[[Soviet Census (1989)|1989 Census]]\n|data3=600,623<ref name=\"1989Census\">{{ru-pop-ref|1989Census}}</ref>\n|label4=[[Soviet Census (1979)|1979 Census]]\n|data4=527,848<ref name=\"1979Census\">{{ru-pop-ref|1979Census}}</ref>\n}}\n[[File:Kitchen-21-Russia-mid-Amur-2830.jpg|thumb|Native villages near the site of the future Khabarovsk according to an English map of 1773. The village closest to today's Khabarovsk is labeled \"Hitcha\". Maack's \"Cape Kyrma\" site (thought by B.P. Polyakov to be the site of Stepanov's Kosogorsky Ostrog) is \"Heremo\"]]\n\n'''Khabarovsk''' ({{lang-rus|\u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0301\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a|a=\u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a.ogg|r=Khabarovsk|p=x\u0250\u02c8bar\u0259fsk}}) is the largest [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|city]] and the [[administrative center]] of [[Khabarovsk Krai]], [[Russia]],<ref name=\"Ref945\">Law #109</ref> located {{convert|30|km|sp=us}} from the [[China\u2013Russia border|Chinese border]], at the [[confluence]] of the [[Amur River|Amur]] and [[Ussuri River]]s, about {{convert|800|km|sp=us}} north of [[Vladivostok]]. The city was the administrative center of the [[Far Eastern Federal District]] of Russia from 2002 until December 2018, when Vladivostok took over that role.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://meduza.io/news/2018/12/13/putin-perenes-stolitsu-dalnevostochnogo-federalnogo-okruga-vo-vladivostok |title=\u041f\u0443\u0442\u0438\u043d \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0435\u0441 \u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0443 \u0414\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0444\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0430 \u0432\u043e \u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a|website=meduza.io|access-date=2018-12-13}}</ref> It is the largest city in the [[Russian Far East]], having overtaken [[Vladivostok]] in 2015. As of the [[Russian Census (2010)|2010 Census]], its population was&nbsp;577,441.<ref name=\"2010Census\">{{ru-pop-ref|2010Census}}</ref> It was previously known as ''Khabarovka''&#32;(until 1893).<ref name=\"gr\" />\n\n==History==\n===Earliest Record===\nFrom historical records, it shows the city had been created from the eighth century. The tribe of the Tungusic peoples are the indigenous humans of the vicinity. Later the metropolis changed into named \"Boli\" and turned into controlled by way of historical miners of China. In Tang Dynasty, Boli was the capital of Heishui, called Heishuiduhufu.\n.<ref>hellotravel, https://www.hellotravel.com/russia/khabarovsk</ref> In A.D. 722, [[Emperor Xuanzong of Tang]] (\u5510\u7384\u5b97) established Heishui Protectorate for each [[Heishui Mohe]] tribes to have self-rule. Then, the capital city of this administrative region in the area of Habarovsk had been constructed.<ref>\u300a\u65b0\u5510\u66f8\u00b7\u5317\u72c4\u50b3\u300b\u8a18\u8f09\uff1a\u300c\u9ed1\u6c34\u897f\u5317\u53c8\u6709\u601d\u6155\u90e8\uff0c\u76ca\u5317\u884c\u5341\u65e5\u5f97\u90e1\u5229\u90e8\uff0c\u6771\u5317\u884c\u5341\u65e5\u5f97\u7a9f\u8aaa\u90e8\uff0c\u4ea6\u865f\u5c48\u8a2d\uff0c\u7a0d\u6771\u5357\u884c\u5341\u65e5\u5f97\u83ab\u66f3\u7686\u90e8\u3002\u300d\u3002(The \"New Tang Dynasty Book of Beidi\" records: \"There is also a tribe called \u201cDream Tribe\u201d in the northwest of Heishui, Yibei travels on the 10th days to the \u201cCounty Tribe\u201d, and the northeast travels on the 10th days to the \u201cCave Tribe\u201d. 10th days to the \u201cMo Mo Tribe\u201d)</ref><ref>\u5510\u7384\u5b97\u5c01\u9ed1\u6c34\u90e8\u914b\u957f\u502a\u5c5e\u5229\u7a3d\u4e3a\u52c3\u5229\u5dde\u523a\u53f2\u3002\"\u52c3\u5229\"\u5c31\u662f\u4eca\u9ed1\u9f99\u6c5f\u3001\u4e4c\u82cf\u91cc\u6c5f\u6c47\u5408\u5904 \u9ed1\u6c34\u519b\u548c\u9ed1\u6c34\u90fd\u7763\u5e9c,\u8d50 \u7684\u4f2f\u529b(\u4eca\u82cf\u8054\u5883\u5185\u54c8\u5df4\u7f57\u592b\u65af\u514b). Heilongjiang Provincial Highway Traffic History Editing Office, \"History of Ancient Road Traffic in Heilongjiang\", Published by People's Communications Press 1988, {{ISBN|7-114-00315-3}}. (https://books.google.com.hk/books?id=6704AAAAIAAJ&dq=editions:LCCN90172212&hl=zh-TW)</ref>\n\n===17th-century Russian explorers===\nIn the mid-17th century, the Amur Valley became the scene of [[Russian-Manchu border conflicts|hostilities]] between the Russian [[Cossacks]], trying to expand into the region and to collect tribute from the natives, and the rising [[Manchu people|Manchu]] [[Qing Dynasty]], intent on securing the region for itself.\n\n====Khabarov's Achansk====\n[[File:\u0415\u0440\u043e\u0444\u0435\u0439 \u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432 2.jpg|thumb|Monument to [[Yerofey Khabarov]] in Khabarovsk.]]\n\nThe Russian explorers and raiders of the 1650s set up a number of more or less fortified camps (''[[ostrog (fortress)|ostrog]]s'') on the Amur; most of them were in use for only a few months, and later destroyed. It is usually thought that the first such camp in the general area of today's Khabarovsk was the fortified winter camp named '''Achansk''' ({{lang|ru|\u0410\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a}}) or '''Achansky gorodok''' ({{lang|ru|\u0410\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043a}}), built by the Cossacks of [[Yerofey Khabarov]] in September 1651 after they had sailed to the area from the upper Amur. The fort was named after the local tribe whom Khabarov's people called \"Achans\".<ref>[http://www.inauka.ru/discovery/article35236.html \u0410\u0440\u0445\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438 \u043e\u0431\u043d\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0436\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0435 \u0442\u0430\u0438\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043a. \u0412\u043e\u0437\u043c\u043e\u0436\u043d\u043e, \u044d\u0442\u043e \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u0435 \u0440\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0435 \u043f\u043e\u0441\u0435\u043b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0432 \u0434\u0430\u043d\u043d\u043e\u043c \u0440\u0435\u0433\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0435] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060525063941/http://www.inauka.ru/discovery/article35236.html |date=May 25, 2006 }} (Mysterious fort found by archaeologists on the Amur. Possibly, this is the first Russian settlement in this region) {{in lang|ru}}</ref><ref name=gai>\u041e\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0430 \u0413\u0430\u0439\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0434\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 (Oksana Gaynutdinova) [http://www.amursk.ru/az/05/1130/r2.htm \u0417\u0430\u0433\u0430\u0434\u043a\u0430 \u0410\u0447\u0430\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043a\u0430] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070813035909/http://www.amursk.ru/az/05/1130/r2.htm |date=August 13, 2007 }} (The mystery of Fort Achansk)</ref> Already on October 8 the fort was unsuccessfully attacked by joint forces of Achans and [[Duchers]] (who had good reasons to hate the Cossacks, due to their rather heavy-handed [[yasak|tribute]]-extraction tactics<ref name=izvet>B.P. Polevoy (\u0411.\u041f. \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439), [http://www.vostlit.info/Texts/Dokumenty/Russ/XVII/1640-1660/Poljakov/pred.htm  \u0418\u0437\u0432\u0435\u0442\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0447\u0435\u043b\u043e\u0431\u0438\u0442\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0421. \u0412. \u041f\u043e\u043b\u044f\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0430 1653 \u0433. \u0438 \u0435\u0435 \u0437\u043d\u0430\u0447\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435 \u0434\u043b\u044f \u0430\u0440\u0445\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0432 \u041f\u0440\u0438\u0430\u043c\u0443\u0440\u044c\u044f] (S.V. Polyakov's denouncing letter (1653), and its significance for the archaeologists of the Amur Valley), in: \u0420\u0443\u0441\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0432\u043e\u043f\u0440\u043e\u0445\u043e\u0434\u0446\u044b \u043d\u0430 \u0414\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0435\u043c \u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043a\u0435 \u0432 XVII-XIX \u0432\u0432. (\u0418\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u043a\u043e-\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0435\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0438\u0441\u0441\u043b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f) (''First Russian explorers in the Far East in the 17th-19th centuries: Historical and archaeological research'' - B.P.Polevoy's preface to the document), vol. 2, Vladivostok, Russian Academy of Sciences, 1995. (This article also contains references to Polevoy's earlier publications) {{in lang|ru}}</ref>), while many Russians were away fishing.<ref name=gai/> In late November, Khabarov's people undertook a three-day campaign against the local chief Zhakshur (\u0416\u0430\u043a\u0448\u0443\u0440) (whose name is also known in a more Russian version, Zaksor (\u0417\u0430\u043a\u0441\u043e\u0440)), collecting a large amount of tribute and announcing that the locals were now subjects of the Russian Czar. Similar campaign was waged later in winter against the Ducher chief Nechiga (\u041d\u0435\u0447\u0438\u0433\u0430), farther away from Achansk.<ref name=gai/>\n\nOn March&nbsp;24 (or&nbsp;26), 1652, Fort Achansk was attacked by [[Manchu people|Manchu]] cavalry, led by [[Ninguta]]'s commander Haise, reinforced by Ducher auxiliaries, but the Cossacks stood their ground in a day-long battle and even managed to seize the attackers' [[Medieval warfare#Supply trains|supply train]].<ref name=gai/> Once the ice on the Amur broke in the spring of 1652, Khabarov's people destroyed their fort and sailed away.<ref name=gai/>\n\nThe exact location of Khabarov's Achansk has long been a subject for the debate among Russian historians and geographers.<ref name=izvet/><ref name=koso>\u0411.\u041f. \u041f\u043e\u043b\u0435\u0432\u043e\u0439 (B.P. Polevoy) [http://ostrog.ucoz.ru/publikacii_2/4_53.htm \u041e \u043f\u043e\u0434\u043b\u0438\u043d\u043d\u043e\u043c \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043f\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0436\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0438 \u041a\u043e\u0441\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0440\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0430 50-\u0445 \u0433\u0433. XVII \u0432\u0435\u043a\u0430] (About the true location of the Kosogorsky ''Ostrog'' of the 1650s) {{in lang|ru}}</ref> A number of locations, both upstream and downstream of today's Khabarovsk, have been proposed since [[Richard Maack]], one of the first Russian scholars to visit the region, identified Achansk in 1859 with the ruins on Cape Kyrma, which is located on the southern (Chinese) shore of the Amur, upstream of Khabarovsk.<ref name=izvet/> The most widely accepted point of view is probably that of [[Boris Petrovich Polevoy|Boris Polevoy]], who believed that Khabarov's Achansk was located in the [[Nani people|Nanai]] village later known as Odzhal-[[Lake Bolon|Bolon]] ({{lang-ru|\u041e\u0434\u0436\u0430\u043b-\u0411\u043e\u043b\u043e\u043d\u044c}}), located on the left bank of the Amur, closer to [[Amursk]] than to Khabarovsk. One of his arguments was that both Khabarov's Achan (sometimes also spelled by the explorer as Otshchan, \u041e\u0442\u0449\u0430\u043d), and Wuzhala (\u4e4c\u624e\u62c9) of the Chinese records of the 1652 engagement are based on the name of the [[Nanais|Nanai]] clan \"Odzhal\" (\u041e\u0434\u0436\u0430\u043b), corresponding to the 20th-century name of the village as well. (The name of the clan was also written as \"Uzala\", as in the name of its best-known member, [[Dersu Uzala]]).<ref name=izvet/>\n\nPolevoy's view appeared to gain wide support among the Russian geographer community; petitioned by the Amur Branch of the [[Russian Geographical Society]], the [[Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic|Russian Government]] renamed the village of Odzhal to Achan in 1977, to celebrate its connection with Khabarov's raid.<ref name=izvet/>\n\nAs to the Cape Kyrma ruins, thought by Maack to be the remains of Achansk, B.P. Polevoy identified them as the remains of another ''ostrog'' - namely, Kosogorsky Ostrog, where [[Onufriy Stepanov]] stayed a few years later.<ref name=koso/>\n\n===Qing Empire===\nAfter the [[Treaty of Nerchinsk]] (1689), the area became an uncontested part of the [[Qing Empire]] for the next century and a half. Modern historical maps of the Qing period published in China mark the site of future Khabarovsk as B\u00f3l\u00ec ({{zh|s=\u4f2f\u529b}}). All of the middle and lower Amur region was nominally part of the [[Jilin]] Province, run first out of [[Ninguta]] and later out of [[Jilin City]].\n\nFrench [[Jesuit missions in China|Jesuit]]s who sailed along the [[Ussury]] and the [[Amur River|Amur]] in 1709 prepared the first more or less precise map of the region. According to them, the indigenous Nanai people were living on the [[Ussury]] and on the Amur down to the mouth of the [[Anyuy River (Khabarovsk Krai)|Dondon River]] (i.e., in the region including the site of the future Khabarovsk). These people were known to the Chinese as ''Yupi Dazi'' (\"Fish skin Tartars\").<ref name=halde7>{{cite book|last=Du Halde|first= Jean-Baptiste|title= Description g\u00e9ographique, historique, chronologique, politique et physique de l'empire de la Chine et de la Tartarie chinoise|volume=Volume IV|publisher= P.G. Lemercier|location=Paris\n|year= 1735|url= http://web2.bium.univ-paris5.fr/livanc/?cote=00992x04&do=chapitre|page=7|authorlink= Jean-Baptiste Du Halde}} Numerous later editions are available as well, including one [https://books.google.com/books?id=1pcsAAAAYAAJ on Google Books]</ref>\n\n===From Khabarovka to Khabarovsk===\n[[File:Khabarovsk - residence of the governor-general of Eastern Siberia LCCN2004708062.jpg|thumb|left|Khabarovsk - residence of the governor-general of Eastern Siberia 1895]]\n\nIn 1858, the area was ceded to Russia under the [[Treaty of Aigun]]. The Russians founded the military outpost of '''Khabarovka''' ({{lang|ru|\u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0301\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0430}}),{{citation needed|date=May 2010}} named after [[Yerofey Khabarov]]. The post later became an important industrial center for the region. Town status was granted in 1880; in 1893, it was given its present name.<ref name=\"gr\">{{cite book|title=\u042d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f \u0413\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438|year=2003|publisher=\u0411\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0448\u0430\u044f \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u042d\u043d\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u043e\u043f\u0435\u0434\u0438\u044f|location=Moscow|isbn=5-7107-7399-9|page=503}}</ref>\n\nIn 1894, a department of [[Russian Geographical Society]] was formed in Khabarovsk and to found libraries, theatres and museums in the city. Since then, Khabarovsk's cultural life has flourished. Much of the local indigenous history has been well preserved in the Regional Lore Museum and Natural History Museum and in places like near the [[Nani people|Nanai]] settlement of [[Sikachi-Alyan]], where cliff drawings from more than 13,000 years ago can be found. The Khabarovsk Art Museum exhibits a rare collection of old Russian icons.\n\nIn 1916, the [[Khabarovsk Bridge]] across the Amur was completed, allowing [[Trans-Siberian Railway|Trans-Siberian]] trains to cross the river without using [[train ferry|ferries]] (or temporary rail tracks over the frozen river in winter).\n\n===Soviet era===\nAfter the defeat of Japan in [[World War II]],  Khabarovsk was the site of the [[Khabarovsk War Crime Trials]], in which twelve former members of the Japanese [[Kwantung Army]] and [[Unit 731]] were put on [[trial (law)|trial]] for the manufacture and use of [[biological weapons]] during World War II.\n\nChinese Emperor [[Puyi]], captured by Soviet troops in [[Manchuria]], was relocated to Khabarovsk and lived there from 1945 up to 1950, when he was returned to China.<ref>http://khv9923.narod.ru/His_last_translator.pdf</ref>\n\nWhen Japan fell in September 1945 the United States reached an agreement with Stalin to build two U.S. Naval Advance Bases (Fleet Weather Centrals) in the USSR.<ref>The 114th CB cruisebook, 1946, U.S.Navy Seabee Museum Archives, Port Hueneme, Ca, p.123-125 [https://books.google.com/books?id=4nwmm4QfSXQC&pg=PA123&lpg=PA123&dq=Construction+battalion+114+Russia&source=bl&ots=4R8idRsfGg&sig=xUpg07nNNod8KosWiOdp-fOj_u0&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwishKHEuPLdAhWn64MKHQfOB6IQ6AEwAXoECAgQAQ#v=onepage&q=Construction%20battalion%20114%20Russia&f=false]</ref> The U.S built one 10 miles outside [[Petropavlovsk-Kamchatsky]] on the [[Kamchatka Peninsula]] with the code name TAMA.<ref name= \"Yanks\">Yanks in Siberia: U.S. Navy Weather Stations in Soviet East Asia, 1945, G. Patrick March, Pacific Historical Review, Vol. 57, No. 3 (Aug., 1988), pp. 327-342, Published by: University of California Press.[https://www.jstor.org/stable/3640708?seq=9#metadata_info_tab_contents]</ref>  The other was 20 miles outside Khabarovsk in buildings provided by the Soviets, code-named MOKO.<ref name= \"Yanks\"/>  For mail Khabarovsk was assigned  U.S.Navy number 1168,  FPO San Francisco.<ref>US Navy Abbreviations of World War II, the Navy Department Library, U.S. Navy web site, Published:Thu Jul 23 14:45:40 EDT 2015 [https://www.history.navy.mil/research/library/online-reading-room/title-list-alphabetically/u/us-navy-abbreviations-of-ww2/navy-numbers.html]</ref>  The American use of these two bases was short-lived.\n\nOn 5 November 1956, the first phase of the city [[tram]] was commissioned. The Khabarovsk television studio began broadcasting in 1960. On 1 September 1967, the Khabarovsk Institute of Physical Education, now the [[Far Eastern State Academy of Physical Culture]], opened. On 14 January 1971 Khabarovsk was awarded the [[Order of October Revolution]]. In 1975 the first stage of the urban [[Tram|trolley]] opened. In 1976 the city hosted an international ice hockey tournament with the ball for the prize of the newspaper ''[[Sovietskaya Rossia]]''. In 1981 the [[Bandy World Championship 1981|Bandy World Championship]] was played in the city.\n\n===Russian Federation===\nIn 1996, Khabarovsk held its first [[Elections in Russia|mayoral elections]]. Paul D. Filippov, whose candidacy was supported by Governor [[Viktor Ishayev]], was defeated. In 1998, reconstruction of the [[Lenin Square, Khabarovsk|central square]] of Khabarovsk was completed. In May 2000, [[President of Russia]], [[Vladimir Putin]], decreed that new federal districts be formed, and Khabarovsk became the center of the [[Far Eastern Federal District]].\n\nIn 2006, the Center for Cardiovascular Surgery, a high-tech medical center, was constructed according to a Russian [[National Priority Projects|national health project]]. In 2008, the train station was completely renovated, and the adjacent square was reconstructed to include fountains and an underground passage. In 2009, Khabarovsk hosted the [[Russia\u2013European Union relations|EU-Russia summit]]. In 2010, the city hosted a meeting of the Great Circle of Ussuri [[Cossacks]]. On 3 November 2012, Khabarovsk was awarded the [[Awards and decorations of the Russian Federation|honorary title]] of \"[[City of Military Glory]]\".\n\n==Administrative and municipal status==\nKhabarovsk is the [[administrative center]] of the [[krai]]<ref name=\"Ref945\" /> and, within the [[subdivisions of Russia#Administrative divisions|framework of administrative divisions]], it also serves as the administrative center of [[Khabarovsky District]],<ref name=\"OKATO\">{{OKATO reference|08 255}}</ref> even though it is not a part of it.<ref name=\"Ref50\">Resolution #143-pr</ref> As an administrative division, it is incorporated separately as the '''[[city of federal subject significance|city of krai significance]] of Khabarovsk'''\u2014an administrative unit with the status equal to that of the [[administrative divisions of Khabarovsk Krai|districts]].<ref name=\"Ref50\" /> As a [[subdivisions of Russia#Municipal divisions|municipal division]], the city of krai significance of Khabarovsk is incorporated as '''Khabarovsk Urban Okrug'''.<ref name=\"Ref739\">Law #177</ref>\n\n==Geography==\n[[File:Txu-oclc-6614368-nm53-11.jpg|thumb|left|Khabarovsk (1950)]]\n\n===Climate===\n{{Climate chart\n|Khabarovsk\n|-23.5 |-15.7 |  14\n|-19.7 |-10.7 |  11\n|-11.0 |- 1.5 |  22\n|  0.1 | 10.4 |  44\n|  7.1 | 18.6 |  61\n| 13.0 | 23.9 |  72\n| 16.8 | 26.6 | 133\n| 15.9 | 24.8 | 153\n|  9.2 | 19.1 |  79\n|  1.0 | 10.0 |  50\n|-10.6 |- 3.1 |  26\n|-20.6 |-13.5 |  17\n|float=right\n|clear=\n|source=Pogoda i Klimat (Weather and Climate)<ref name=\"pogoda\">{{cite web\n|url=http://www.pogodaiklimat.ru/climate/31735.htm|title=Pogoda.ru.net|accessdate=November 30, 2015|publisher=|language=Russian}}</ref>\n}}\nKhabarovsk experiences a monsoonal dry-winter [[humid continental climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''Dwb'' borders on ''Dwa'').\n\nThe average annual [[precipitation]] is {{convert|682|mm|sp=us}}, mainly concentrated in the summer. In a few years, November to March hardly receive any precipitation. The driest year was 2001 with only {{convert|381|mm|sp=us}} of precipitation and the wettest was 1981 when {{convert|1105|mm|sp=us}} of precipitation fell. The wettest month was August 1981 with a total precipitation of {{convert|434|mm|sp=us}}. Snowfall is common, though light, with an average maximum snow height of {{convert|16|cm|sp=us}}.\n\nThe city's extreme climate sees average highs and lows vary by around {{convert|50|C-change}} per year. The average temperature in January is {{convert|-19.8|C}} and the average for July is {{convert|+21.3|C}}. Extremes have ranged from {{convert|-40|C}} in January 2011 to {{convert|+36.4|C}} in June 2010.<ref name=\"pogoda\" />\n\n{{Weather box\n|location=Khabarovsk\n|metric first=yes\n|single line=yes\n|Jan record high C=0.6\n|Feb record high C=6.3\n|Mar record high C=17.0\n|Apr record high C=28.6\n|May record high C=31.5\n|Jun record high C=36.4\n|Jul record high C=35.7\n|Aug record high C=35.6\n|Sep record high C=29.8\n|Oct record high C=25.8\n|Nov record high C=15.5\n|Dec record high C=6.6\n|year record high C=36.4\n|Jan high C=-15.7\n|Feb high C=-10.7\n|Mar high C=-1.5\n|Apr high C=10.4\n|May high C=18.6\n|Jun high C=23.9\n|Jul high C=26.6\n|Aug high C=24.8\n|Sep high C=19.1\n|Oct high C=10.0\n|Nov high C=-3.1\n|Dec high C=-13.5\n|year high C=7.4\n|Jan mean C=-19.8\n|Feb mean C=-15.4\n|Mar mean C=-6.4\n|Apr mean C=4.8\n|May mean C = 12.4\n|Jun mean C = 18.1\n|Jul mean C = 21.3\n|Aug mean C = 19.9\n|Sep mean C = 13.7\n|Oct mean C = 5.1\n|Nov mean C = -7.2\n|Dec mean C = -17.3\n|year mean C = 2.4\n|Jan low C = -23.5\n|Feb low C = -19.7\n|Mar low C = -11.0\n|Apr low C = 0.1\n|May low C = 7.1\n|Jun low C = 13.0\n|Jul low C = 16.8\n|Aug low C = 15.9\n|Sep low C = 9.2\n|Oct low C = 1.0\n|Nov low C = -10.6\n|Dec low C = -20.6\n|year low C = -1.9\n|Jan record low C = -40.0\n|Feb record low C = -35.1\n|Mar record low C = -28.9\n|Apr record low C = -15.1\n|May record low C = -3.1\n|Jun record low C = 2.2\n|Jul record low C = 6.8\n|Aug record low C = 4.9\n|Sep record low C = -3.3\n|Oct record low C = -15.6\n|Nov record low C = -27.4\n|Dec record low C = -36.7\n|year record low C = -40.0\n|precipitation colour=green\n|Jan precipitation mm = 14\n|Feb precipitation mm = 11\n|Mar precipitation mm = 22\n|Apr precipitation mm = 44\n|May precipitation mm = 61\n|Jun precipitation mm = 72\n|Jul precipitation mm = 133\n|Aug precipitation mm = 153\n|Sep precipitation mm = 79\n|Oct precipitation mm = 50\n|Nov precipitation mm = 26\n|Dec precipitation mm = 17\n|year precipitation mm = 682\n|Jan humidity = 75\n|Feb humidity = 72\n|Mar humidity = 68\n|Apr humidity = 63\n|May humidity = 65\n|Jun humidity = 74\n|Jul humidity = 79\n|Aug humidity = 83\n|Sep humidity = 78\n|Oct humidity