3b\u043b\u0435\u0439\u0431\u0443\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \u043f\u043b\u043e\u0449\u0430\u0434\u0438 \u041b\u0435\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u04441.JPG|thumb|[[Trolleybus]] near Lenina Square]]\n[[File:\u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a, \u043b\u0435\u0442\u043e\u043c \u043d\u0430 \u043d\u0430\u0431\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0436\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0410\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0430.JPG|thumb|Amur waterfront]]\n\nThe city is principal railway center and is located along the [[Trans-Siberian Railway]]; the rail distance of [[Khabarovsk railway station]] from [[Moscow]] is {{convert|8523|km|sp=us}}.\n\nKhabarovsk is served by the [[Khabarovsk Novy Airport]] with international flights to [[East Asia]], [[Southeast Asia]], [[European Russia]], and [[Central Asia]].\n\nRoad links include the [[Trans-Siberian Highway]] ([[M58 highway (Russia)|M58]] and [[M60 highway (Russia)|M60]] Highways), and water transport links are provided by the [[Amur River]] and [[Ussuri River]].\n\nPublic transport includes: [[Trams in Khabarovsk|tram]] (8 routes); trolleybus (4 routes); bus and fixed-route taxi ([[marshrutka]], approximately 100 routes).\n\n==Education==\nThere are the following institutions of higher education in Khabarovsk:<ref>[http://adm.khv.ru/invest2.nsf/edd578ced75448e2ca256524001a00c2/6ea7ef189fc9473fca25665100159738?OpenDocument The Institutions of Higher Education in Khabarovsk Krai] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051228031353/http://www.adm.khv.ru/invest2.nsf/edd578ced75448e2ca256524001a00c2/6ea7ef189fc9473fca25665100159738?OpenDocument |date=December 28, 2005 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.russia-ukraine-travel.com/khabarovsk-universities.html The Universities in Khabarovsk]</ref>\n*[[Pacific National University]] (former Khabarovsk State University of Technology)\n*[[Far Eastern State University of Humanities]] (former Khabarovsk State Teachers Training University)\n*[[Far Eastern State Medical University]]\n*[[Khabarovsk State Academy of Economics and Law]]\n*[[Far Eastern State Transport University]]\n*[[Far Eastern Academy of Public Service]]\n*[[Far Eastern State Physical Education University]]\n*[[Khabarovsk State Institute of Arts and Culture]]\n\n==Tourism==\n[[File:\u0412\u0435\u0447\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043e\u0433\u043e\u043d\u044c, \u0437\u0430\u0436\u0436\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043e\u0442 \u043f\u043b\u0430\u043c\u0435\u043d\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043f\u0435\u0447\u0438 \u0437\u0430\u0432\u043e\u0434\u0430 \"\u0410\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0430\u043b\u044c\", \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0432\u0435\u0437\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0437 \u041a\u043e\u043c\u0441\u043e\u043c\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0430-\u043d\u0430-\u0410\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0435.jpg|thumb|A war memorial.]]\nA key street in Khabarovsk is the broad [[Amursky Boulevard]] with its many shops and a local market. The city's five districts stretch for {{convert|45|km|sp=us}} along the Amur River. The similar boulevard - Ussuryisky is located between the two main streets Muravyov-Amursky and Lenin street and runs to the city's artificial lakes (Gorodskie Prudi) with the sport complex Platinum Arena. The lakes are famous for their fountains with the light show. The [[Military History Museum of the Far Eastern Military District]] is located in the city, the only such museum in the Russian Far East.<ref>{{cite web|last=Kokurin|first=Boris|title=\u0412\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u043c\u0443\u0437\u0435\u0439 \u0432 \u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0442\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u0441\u044f \u043a \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0442\u0438\u044e|url=https://www.hab.kp.ru/daily/26199.2/3085703/|website=[[Komsomolskaya Pravda]]|accessdate=1 November 2017|date=25 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nRecently,{{when|date=April 2017}} there have been renovations in the city's central part, rebuilding with historical perspective. There is a walking tour from the [[Vladimir Lenin|Lenin]] Square to Utyos on Amur via [[Nikolay Muravyov-Amursky|Muravyov-Amursky]] Street, where visitors find traditional Russian cuisine restaurants and shops with souvenirs.{{citation needed|date=April 2017}} There are a number of night clubs and pubs in this area.\nIn Wintertime ice sculptures are on display on the cities squares and parks. Artists come from as far as [[Harbin]] in China.\n\nUnlike [[Vladivostok]], the city has never been closed to foreigners, despite it being the headquarters of the [[Far East Military District]], and retains its historically international flavor. Once the capital of the [[Soviet Far East]] (from 1926 to 1938), since the demise of the [[Soviet Union]], it has experienced an increased Asian presence. It is estimated that over one million Chinese travel to and through Khabarovsk yearly, and foreign investment by [[Japan]]ese and [[South Korea|Korean]] corporations has grown in recent years. The city has a multi-story shopping mall and about a dozen hotels.\n\nAleksandr Fedosov, the Khabarovsk Krai Minister of Culture, estimates that the city became more attractive to tourists following the [[2015 Bandy World Championship]].<ref name=\"bandy-vm2018.ru\">[http://bandy-vm2018.ru/en/news/world-championship-khabarovsk-national-event-year World Championship in Khabarovsk - \"The National Event of the Year\"]</ref>\n\nKhabarovsk is the closest major city to [[Birobidzhan]], which is the [[administrative center]] of the [[Jewish Autonomous Oblast]], [[Russia]], located on the [[Trans-Siberian Railway]], close to the [[China\u2013Russia border|border with China]]. The [[Jewish Autonomous Oblast]] is a [[federal subjects of Russia|federal subject]] of [[Russia]] in the [[Russian Far East]], bordering [[Khabarovsk Krai]] and [[Amur Oblast]] in Russia and [[Heilongjiang]] province in [[China]]. Its [[administrative center]] is the [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|town]] of [[Birobidzhan]], and it is the only region in the world in that [[Yiddish]] is the official language. Khabarovsk provides the closest major airport to [[Birobidzhan]], which is [[Khabarovsk Novy Airport]] (KHV / UHHH), 198&nbsp;km from the center of [[Birobidzhan]].\n\n==Military==\n[[File:2017 \u041c\u0435\u0436\u0434\u0443\u043d\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0432\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e-\u043c\u0443\u0437\u044b\u043a\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u043e\u043c\u0443 \u0444\u0435\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0432\u0430\u043b\u044e \u00ab\u0410\u043c\u0443\u0440\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0432\u043e\u043b\u043d\u044b\u00bb 06.jpg|thumb|The Khabarovsk Honour Guard.]]\nThe headquarters of the [[Russian Ground Forces]]'s [[Eastern Military District]] is located at 15 Serysheva Street. The district was preceded by the [[Far Eastern Military District]], which was located in the same location. The following component units of the district are stationed in the city:\n\n* 104th Cluj Headquarters Brigade \n* Honour Guard Company of the Khabarovsk Garrison<ref>http://www.bestmagazine.ru/issues/2014-05/rota-pochetnogo-karaula</ref><ref>http://mbpolyakov.ru/index.php?docid=468474</ref>\n* 17th Independent Electronic Warfare Brigade \n* 118th Independent Pontoon-Bridge Railway Battalion\n* [[392nd District Training Centre|392nd Pacific Training Center for Junior Specialists]] \n* [[11th Air and Air Defence Forces Army]]\n* [[Military Band of the Eastern Military District]]\n\nAll 5 of these units make up the Khabarovsk Garrison. The [[Russian Navy]]'s [[Pacific Fleet (Russia)|Pacific Fleet]] maintains a presence in the city as well. There is also an air base located {{convert|3|km|abbr=on}} to the east of the city. The main public relations asset for the military in the city is the [[Military History Museum of the Far Eastern Military District]] and the [[Military Band of the Eastern Military District|district military band]].\n\n==Sports==\n[[File:1981. \u0427\u0435\u043c\u043f\u0438\u043e\u043d\u0430\u0442 \u043c\u0438\u0440\u0430 \u043f\u043e \u0445\u043e\u043a\u043a\u0435\u044e \u0441 \u043c\u044f\u0447\u043e\u043c.jpg|thumb|[[Postage stamp|Stamp]] depicting [[1981 Bandy World Championship]] in Khabarovsk]]\n[[File:\u0423\u0424\u0425\u041c\u0420 IMG 0475.jpg|right|thumb|A corner during the final of the [[2015 Bandy World Championship]]]]\n\n*[[Amur Khabarovsk]], a professional ice hockey club of the international [[Kontinental Hockey League]] and plays its home games at the [[Platinum Arena]]. It used to be the easternmost-based team in the league until [[Admiral Vladivostok]] joined the KHL in 2013 as an expansion team.\n*[[FC SKA-Khabarovsk]], a professional [[association football]] team playing in the [[Russian Premier League]], the top tier of Russian association football.\n*[[SKA-Neftyanik]], a professional bandy club which plays in the top-tier [[Russian Bandy Super League]] at its own indoor venue [[Arena Yerofey]]. It is both the easternmost and southernmost team in the top division. In the [[2016\u201317 Russian Bandy Super League|2016-17 season]] the club became [[List of Russian bandy champions|Russian champion]] for the first time.<ref>[https://translate.google.co.uk/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.rusbandy.ru%2Fnews%2F10616]</ref> As of 2019 the team has won the title three years in a row.<ref>[http://skabandy.ru/index.php?r=post&id=285 Threefold Russian Bandy Championship winners!]</ref>\n\n===International events===\nThe city was a host to the [[1981 Bandy World Championship]].  It also hosted the [[2015 Bandy World Championship]], which was visited by Prime Minister [[Dmitry Medvedev]].<ref>[https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&u=http://www.rusbandy.ru/news/7059/&prev=search rusbandy.ru]</ref> 21 teams were expected,<ref>[https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fitar-tass.com%2Fsport%2F1281154&sandbox=1 Itar-Tass Sport]</ref> which would have been 4 more than the then record-making 17 (now it's 18) from [[2014 Bandy World Championship|the 2014 tournament]]. In the end, [[China national bandy team|China]] was the only newcomer, while [[Canada national bandy team|Canada]] and [[Ukraine national bandy team|Ukraine]] withdrew, the latter for [[Politics and sport|political reasons]]. Khabarovsk organised [[2018 Bandy World Championship|the 2018 tournament]] as well, but not Division B that time around, which was held in Chinese [[Harbin]].<ref>[https://translate.google.co.uk/translate?hl=en&sl=ru&tl=en&u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.rusbandy.ru%2Fnews%2F10347%2F rusbandy.ru]</ref> The event was named by the [[Federal Agency for Tourism (Russia)|Federal Agency for Tourism]] as one of the best 200 events of the year.<ref name=\"bandy-vm2018.ru\"/>\n\n====Important visits====\nA delegation from the [[2022 Winter Olympics]] organising committee will visit Khabarovsk to watch matches in the bandy league, since they are considering letting bandy be a part of the programme in 2022.<ref>[https://translate.google.se/translate?hl=sv&sl=ru&u=http://www.dvnovosti.ru/sport/2017/02/04/61886/ dvnovosti.ru/sport 2017-02-04]</ref>\n\n==People==\n*[[Oleksandr Aliyev]], association football player\n*[[Sergei Bodrov]], filmmaker\n*[[Evgeny Grachev]], ice hockey player\n*[[Mikhail Grigorenko]], ice hockey player\n*[[Alexandra Ivanovskaya]], 2005 Miss Russia winner\n*[[Alexander Mogilny]], ice hockey player\n*[[Evgeni Plushenko]], Olympic figure skater\n*[[Ivan Skobrev]], speed skater\n*[[Andrei Tchmil]], professional cyclist\n*[[Efim Zelmanov]], mathematician\n*[[Ivan Koumaev]], dancer\n*[[Andrey Zamkovoy]], boxer\n*[[Vita Sidorkina]], model\n*[[Vladimir Volegov]], painter\n*[[Denis Kenzo]], music producer\n*[[Daria Usacheva]], figure skater\n\n==Twin towns \u2013 sister cities==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in Russia}}\n\nKhabarovsk is [[sister cities|twinned]] with:<ref>{{cite web |title=\u0413\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430-\u043f\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430\u0442\u0438\u043c\u044b|url=https://www.khabarovskadm.ru/tourism/turisticheskiy-khabarovsk/goroda-porbatimy/index.php?ELEMENT_ID=109647|website=khabarovskadm.ru|publisher=Khabarovsk|language=ru|accessdate=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n{{div col|colwidth=17em}}\n*{{flagicon|JPN}} [[Niigata (city)|Niigata]], Japan (1965)\n*{{flagicon|USA}} [[Portland, Oregon|Portland]], United States (1988)\n*{{flagicon|CAN}} [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]], Canada (1990)\n*{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Harbin]], China (1993)\n*{{flagicon|KOR}} [[Bucheon]], South Korea (2002)\n*{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Sanya]], China (2011)\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Awards==\n*Khabarovsk placed first in different categories of \"Most Developed and Comfortable City of Russia\" in 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rg.ru/2007/10/26/gorod-anons.html |title=\u0412 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435 \u043d\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0430 \"\u0421\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0439 \u0431\u043b\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438\" \u2014 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u2014 \u0421\u0435\u0433\u043e\u0434\u043d\u044f \u0432 \u041c\u043e\u0441\u043a\u0432\u0435 \u043d\u0430 \u0412\u0412\u0426 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0448\u043b\u0430 \u0446\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043c\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043d\u0430\u0433\u0440\u0430\u0436\u0434\u0435\u043d\u0438\u044f \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0432 \u0412\u0441\u0435\u0440\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043a\u043e\u043d\u043a\u0443\u0440\u0441\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0437\u0432\u0430\u043d\u0438\u0435 \"\u0421\u0430\u043c\u044b\u0439 \u0431\u043b\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438\" \u0437\u0430 2006 \u0433\u043e\u0434 |publisher=Rg.ru |date= |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref> 2008<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rg.ru/2009/10/05/reg-dvostok/gorod-anons.html |title=\u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a \u0432\u043d\u043e\u0432\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d \u0441\u0430\u043c\u044b\u043c \u0431\u043b\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043c \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 \u2014 \u041d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u0414\u043e\u0440\u043e\u043d\u0438\u043d\u0430 \u2014 \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u0430\u0437\u0435\u0442\u0430 \u2014 \u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a \u0432\u043d\u043e\u0432\u044c \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0437\u043d\u0430\u043d \u0441\u0430\u043c\u044b\u043c \u0431\u043b\u0430\u0433\u043e\u0443\u0441\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0435\u043d\u043d\u044b\u043c \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u043e\u043c \u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0438 |publisher=Rg.ru |date=2012-06-21 |accessdate=2013-03-26}}</ref> and 2009.\n*In 2010, Khabarovsk won the second place in the [[Forbes]] list of most suitable cities for private business in Russia.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://hbr.moigorod.ru/news/details.asp?n=2146407918 |title=\u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a \u0437\u0430\u043d\u044f\u043b II \u043c\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0432 \u0440\u0435\u0439\u0442\u0438\u043d\u0433\u0435 Forbes - \u041d\u043e\u0432\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0438 |publisher=Hbr.moigorod.ru |accessdate=2013-03-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110817181236/http://hbr.moigorod.ru/news/details.asp?n=2146407918 |archivedate=August 17, 2011 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> First place went to [[Krasnodar]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bolshoy Ussuriysky Island]]\n\n==References==\n===Notes===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Sources===\n*{{Cite Russian law\n|ru_entity=\u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0414\u0443\u043c\u0430\n|ru_type=\u0420\u0435\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435\n|ru_number=856\n|ru_date=28 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2014 \u0433.\n|ru_title=\u041e \u0433\u0438\u043c\u043d\u0435 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u043a\u0440\u0443\u0433\u0430 \"\u0413\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434 \u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\"\n|ru_effective_date=28 \u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044f 2014 \u0433\n|ru_published_in=\"\u0421\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0438\u043a \u043d\u043e\u0440\u043c\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0432\u043d\u044b\u0445 \u0430\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0432 \u0430\u0434\u043c\u0438\u043d\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u0438 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0430 \u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0430 \u0438 \u0425\u0430\u0431\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0432\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0433\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0414\u0443\u043c\u044b\", \u21161\n|ru_published_date=\u044f\u043d\u0432\u0430\u0440\u044c 2014 \u0433\n|ru_url=\n|en_entity=Khabarovsk City Duma\n|en_type=Decision\n|en_number=856\n|en_date=January&nbsp;28, 2014\n|en_title=On the Anthem of the Urban Okrug of \"the City of Khabarovsk\"\n|en_effective_date=January&nbsp;28, 2014\n|en_url=\n}}\n*{{RussiaBasicLawRef|kha|khabarovsk}}\n*{{RussiaAdmMunRef|kha|adm|law}}\n*{{RussiaAdmMunRef|kha|adm|list}}\n*{{RussiaAdmMunRef|kha|mun|list|khabarovsk}}\n*{{RussiaAdmMunRef|kha|mun|list3}}\n*Nikolay P. Kradin. ''It Is Protected by the State: the Monuments of Architecture in Khabarovsk''. Khabarovsk: Chastnaya kollektsiya, 1999. 192 p.&nbsp;{{ISBN|5-7875-0011-3}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Khabarovsk}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n{{Wiktionary|Khabarovsk}}\n\n*[http://khabarovskadm.ru Official website of Khabarovsk]\n*{{Britannica|316006}}\